  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Rigor Declaration">
      Output: 🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL · 📋 REASON: code-impl in BFF (.cs file modification, interface change, tag bff-api, ADR-010+013+029 applicable) — quality gates Step 9.5 required · Proceeding with Step 0...
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Load context">
      Read project CLAUDE.md + spec.md FR-16 + plan.md Wave 3 + task 030 design doc + `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md`.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Verify dependency">
      Confirm `notes/spikes/getconfigschema-design.md` exists. If not, STOP — task 030 must complete first.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Read INodeExecutor interface">
      Open `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Nodes/INodeExecutor.cs`. Mirror the XML doc style.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Create ExecutorConfigSchema record file">
      Create `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Nodes/ExecutorConfigSchema.cs` (or co-locate per task 030 design):
      <![CDATA[
      namespace Sprk.Bff.Api.Services.Ai.Nodes;

      /// <summary>Per FR-16 — typed config schema for a node executor.</summary>
      public sealed record ExecutorConfigSchema(IReadOnlyDictionary<string, ConfigFieldDescriptor> Fields)
      {
          public static readonly ExecutorConfigSchema Empty = new(new Dictionary<string, ConfigFieldDescriptor>());
      }

      public sealed record ConfigFieldDescriptor(
          string Type,
          bool Required,
          object? Default,
          string Description,
          IReadOnlyList<string>? Enum);
      ]]>
      (Exact shape per task 030 design — this is illustrative.)
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Add GetConfigSchema() to INodeExecutor">
      Add the method with XML doc citing FR-16. Default-implementation OR add separately per task 030 design:
      <![CDATA[
      /// <summary>
      /// Returns the typed config schema declaring the shape of `sprk_configjson` this executor accepts.
      /// Per FR-16 / Invariant 5. PlaybookBuilder canvas reads schemas via the executor-config-schemas
      /// endpoint to render typed forms (replacing free-form JSON editing).
      /// Implementations may return <see cref="ExecutorConfigSchema.Empty"/> as a placeholder.
      /// </summary>
      ExecutorConfigSchema GetConfigSchema();
      ]]>
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Make the build pass">
      Option A (default impl on interface): provide a `default` impl returning `ExecutorConfigSchema.Empty`. C# 8+ default interface methods.
      Option B (stub each executor): add `public ExecutorConfigSchema GetConfigSchema() =&gt; ExecutorConfigSchema.Empty;` to all 33 existing executors.
      Pick per task 030 decision. Document the choice in the commit message.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Build">
      Run: dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/
      Goal: 0 errors, 0 NEW warnings.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Run existing tests">
      Run: dotnet test (focus on Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests). Goal: no regression. No new tests added in this task (those land in task 034).
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Verify acceptance">
      Open INodeExecutor.cs + ExecutorConfigSchema.cs in editor; confirm all goal bullets satisfied.
    </step>
    <step order="9.5" name="Quality gates (FULL rigor)">
      Run `/code-review` on changes. Run `/adr-check` against ADR-010 + ADR-013 + ADR-029 + bff-extensions.md.
      Fix any findings before commit.
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Update current-task.md + TASK-INDEX">
      Mark task 031 status complete; advance current-task.md to task 032.
    </step>
    <step order="11" name="Commit">
      Commit INodeExecutor.cs + ExecutorConfigSchema.cs (+ any executor stubs if Option B chosen) with conventional message.
      Example: feat(bff/r7): add INodeExecutor.GetConfigSchema seam (Wave 3 task 031, FR-16)
    </step>
  </steps>

